The dividend yield refers to the percentage of the initial stock price that is given out as dividends. This can be solved by dividing the given dividend by the initial price of the share.

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Dividend yield}&=\dfrac{D_{t+1}}{P_t}
\end{aligned}$$

Where,

$$\begin{aligned}
D_{t+1}&=\text{Dividend gained}\\
P_t&=\text{Initial price of the share}
\end{aligned}$$

The capital gains yield refers to the percentage change between the initial and final prices of the share. This can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Capital gains yield}&=\dfrac{P_{t+1}-P_t}{P_t}
\end{aligned}$$

Where, 

$$\begin{aligned}
P_t&=\text{Initial price of the share/stock}\\
P_{t+1}&=\text{final price of the share/stock}
\end{aligned}$$
